==English==

===Alternative forms===
* [[Academe]]

===Etymology===
* From {{etyl|NL.|en}} {{term|academia|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|Ἀκαδημία|tr=Akadēmia|lang=grc}}; see {{term|academy|lang=en}}. ''Academe'' (frequently capitalized) is a poetic name for the garden or grove near ancient Athens where {{w|Plato}} taught, supposedly named for its former owner, the hero Ἀκάδημος (''{{w|Akademos}};'' Ἑκάδημος, ''Hekademos'').

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈæk.ə.diːm/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæk.əˌdim/}}
* {{rhymes|iːm}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{historical}} The name of the garden in Athens where the academics met. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED>Brown, Lesley, ed. ''The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary.'' 5th. Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2003.</ref>
# {{context|poetic|}} An [[academy]]; a place of learning. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|poetic|}} The [[scholarly]] life, environment, or community. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 19th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# A senior member of the staff at an institution of higher learning; [[pedant]]. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 20th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

====Usage notes====
* Poetic references are often to “the groves of Academe”, a translation of [[w:Horace|Horace’s]] ''inter silvas Academi''.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=NHYXAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA169&dq=%22silvas+Academi%22&lr=&as_brr=1#PRA3-PA169,M1]</ref><ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=nVE3QD1Y5RAC&pg=PA14&dq=%22silvas+Academi%22&lr=&sig=pymz2Xcnaldixpke_6QPFsNSGxk]</ref>
